<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="196" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/2145½</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-17">
                                <hi rend="italic">17 June, 1918</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: There seems to me to emerge
                        from this suggestion<note n="51" xml:id="d196fn1">See telegram of June 13,
                            1918, from the Minister in China, <ref target="frus1918Russiav02#pg_206">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, Russia, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 206</ref>.</note> the shadow of a
                        plan that might be worked, with Japanese and other assistance. These
                            people<note n="52" xml:id="d196fn2">The Czecho-Slovaks.</note> are the
                        cousins of the Russians.</p>
                    <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>W. W.</signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>